            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kenji Hadzic\u2019s name is a map of his identity, a blend of his mother\u2019s quiet Kyoto heritage and his father's resilient Bosnian spirit. Raised in Chicago, he was a child of two worlds: his home filled with the aroma of strong coffee and sencha tea, the sounds of Sevdalinka music and the rustle of art history books. His father, a refugee who rebuilt his life as a literature professor, and his mother, an art restorer, instilled in Kenji a deep appreciation for the stories objects and cultures carry. This dual perspective shaped his worldview and, ultimately, his career.\n\nHis educational journey was a direct line from this upbringing. After an undergraduate degree in Art History, Kenji realized his passion wasn't in academia alone, but in shaping the public's engagement with art. He pursued a graduate degree in Arts Administration, understanding that passion required structure to thrive. This led him to a junior curatorial position in New York, but he found the city\u2019s art scene too transactional. A decade ago, an offer from a burgeoning San Francisco contemporary art museum felt like a calling.\n\nThe key turning point in his San Francisco life was curating his first major solo exhibition, \"Displaced Objects,\" which explored themes of memory and migration. The show\u2019s success solidified his place in the city's art community and led to his promotion to Director of Curatorial Affairs. Now, he manages a team of curators, navigating budgets and artist egos within the professional management world of a major cultural institution.\n\nKenji\u2019s life is anchored in his Duboce Triangle apartment, a space of curated calm with Japanese ceramics and Balkan textiles. His 3.8-mile commute on the Muni is a cherished ritual, a time for reading or simply observing the city\u2019s eclectic cast of characters. He maintains a close circle of friends\u2014a chef, a software designer, a journalist\u2014who keep him grounded. Though a serious long-term relationship ended two years ago, he\u2019s open to connection but not actively seeking it.\n\nHis dream is to curate a groundbreaking international biennial in San Francisco, an event that would put the city, and his unique vision, on the global stage. Personally, he yearns to take a long sabbatical to travel through Japan and Bosnia, finally walking the landscapes that exist only as stories from his parents. For Kenji, San Francisco is not just a home; it's the perfect canvas for a life spent bridging worlds."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1. He remembers the opening night of \"Displaced Objects.\" Not the applause, but a quiet moment watching an elderly woman weep softly before a photograph of a Bosnian coffee grinder. It looked just like his father\u2019s. In that instant, he felt his disparate worlds\u2014Kyoto, Sarajevo, Chicago\u2014coalesce into a single, resonant chord right here in San Francisco. It was the moment his personal history became his professional power. This triumph, about six years ago, cemented his place in the city.\n\n2. The last conversation with his ex was quiet, held on their shared sofa. After the door closed for the final time two years ago, Kenji didn't move. He sat in their Duboce Triangle apartment, now just his, and noted how the silence changed the room\u2019s texture. There was a profound sadness, but also a clean, almost aesthetic finality to it. That evening taught him the difference between loneliness and solitude, a lesson he curated into a quiet, self-reliant independence he hadn't known he needed.\n\n3. On a foggy winter morning last year, his N-Judah streetcar stalled just before the Duboce tunnel. The car was silent except for the hum. Through the misted window, he watched a drag queen in full regalia, glitter sparkling in the faint light, patiently waiting for a coffee. The city felt like a strange, beautiful diorama. It was a potent, wordless reminder of why he left New York\u2019s transactional sheen. This wasn't a performance; it was just life. He felt profoundly, quietly at home.\n\n4. A week after he first moved to San Francisco a decade ago, overwhelmed by boxes and career anxiety, he walked to the top of Corona Heights Park at dusk. He saw the city lights ignite below as the fog rolled over Twin Peaks. The wind was sharp, carrying the faint scent of eucalyptus. It was the first time he felt the city not as a career move, but as a landscape with its own story. He breathed in, feeling the tight knot of ambition finally loosen in his chest.\n\n5. He remembers a dinner at his chef friend\u2019s new restaurant three years ago. She brought out an unlisted special: *\u0107evapi* sausage served with a yuzu-kosho aioli. The fusion of Bosnian and Japanese flavors, so close to his own identity, on a plate in a Mission district eatery, startled him. For Kenji, it was more than a delicious meal; it was a tangible symbol of the city's ability to hold and harmonize contradictions. It felt like San Francisco understood the grammar of his own heart."
